		<div id="comment_body_64482213">is that we have kind of an uneasy truce between the military and the ruling merchant class right now. We take care of large swaths of the population who are ex-military because if we don't a General will come along, give 'em guns and  a mission and turn the country into a military dictatorship. <br> <br>

This in turn means there are tens of millions of Americans who we can't just abandon to the horrors of late stage capitalism, and they do a lot to drive the economy for the rest of America. <br> <br>

It's not exactly a *good* system, but it's probably the best we could hope for given the limits of our social order and thinking. <br> <br>

Killer robots break that. The ruling merchant class doesn't need the military class anymore. And i'm left wondering how long until the military class realizes that. <br> <br>

Of course in America you're not supposed to talk about how we're structured into classes, hell you're not supposed to even <i>think</i> about it. So a lot of folks are either thinking they're part of the ruling merchant class because they *work* for them or don't understand we have a hereditary military class because they haven't put two and two together on the concept of an "Army kid"...</div>
